                <html:p>
A <fr:link href="/gtop-000B/" title="Hausdorff Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000B/" display-uri="gtop-000B" type="local">Hausdorff space</fr:link> is one where distinct points are truly separate — you can always draw non-overlapping <fr:link href="/gtop-0005/" title="Open Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0005/" display-uri="gtop-0005" type="local">open</fr:link> neighbourhoods around them.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Without the Hausdorff property, a sequence can converge to multiple limits simultaneously, and single points might not be <fr:link href="/gtop-0006/" title="Closed Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0006/" display-uri="gtop-0006" type="local">closed</fr:link> sets.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Most spaces encountered naturally (<fr:link href="/gtop-0003/" title="Metric Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0003/" display-uri="gtop-0003" type="local">metric spaces</fr:link>, manifolds, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex>) are Hausdorff. The indiscrete topology is the classic non-Hausdorff example — the only nonempty open set is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> itself, so you can never separate any two points.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
