                <fr:title text="Intuition: Measure vs Metric">Intuition: Measure vs Metric</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
A <html:strong>measure</html:strong> assigns a "size" to a set — how much stuff is in it. Length, area, volume, and probability are all measures.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
A <html:strong>metric</html:strong> assigns a "distance" between two points — how far apart they are.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
They answer fundamentally different questions: measure asks "how big is this region?" while metric asks "how far apart are these two points?"
</html:p>
                <html:p>
A metric is upstream of measure: a <fr:link href="/gtop-0003/" title="Metric Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0003/" display-uri="gtop-0003" type="local">metric</fr:link> defines <fr:link href="/gtop-000S/" title="Open Ball" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000S/" display-uri="gtop-000S" type="local">open balls</fr:link>, which give a <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topology</fr:link>, which give a <fr:link href="/gtop-000K/" title="Borel \sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000K/" display-uri="gtop-000K" type="local">Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link>, which gives sets you can measure. A set can be small in measure but wide in metric (e.g., a thin line segment across a room).
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/boat/" title="Zihang Zeng" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/boat/" display-uri="boat" type="local">Zihang Zeng</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>11</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://boatnotabot.com/todo-0004/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>todo-0004</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/todo-0004/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intuition: \sigma -algebra">Intuition: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
A <fr:link href="/gtop-000M/" title="\sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000M/" display-uri="gtop-000M" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link> is a collection of sets that is closed under the operations you need to do measurement: complements and countable unions.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Think of it as a budget of measurable sets — it decides what you are allowed to measure. Not every subset needs to be included, but whatever is included must be self-consistent: if you can measure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, you can measure "not <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>"; if you can measure <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A_1, A_2, A_3, \ldots ]]></fr:tex>, you can measure their union.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Why not just measure everything? In <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, you cannot assign a consistent length to all subsets (Vitali sets). The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra avoids this by restricting to a well-behaved collection where measurement stays consistent.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
The <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex> specifically means countable — closed under countable unions, not just finite ones. This is what distinguishes it from a plain algebra of sets and is essential for doing limits and integration.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/boat/" title="Zihang Zeng" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/boat/" display-uri="boat" type="local">Zihang Zeng</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>11</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://boatnotabot.com/todo-0005/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>todo-0005</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/todo-0005/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intuition: Borel \sigma -algebra">Intuition: Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
The <fr:link href="/gtop-000K/" title="Borel \sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000K/" display-uri="gtop-000K" type="local">Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link> is what you get by starting from the <fr:link href="/gtop-0005/" title="Open Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0005/" display-uri="gtop-0005" type="local">open sets</fr:link> and asking: what is the smallest <fr:link href="/gtop-000M/" title="\sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000M/" display-uri="gtop-000M" type="local"><fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link> containing all of them?
</html:p>
                <html:p>
The <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topology</fr:link> decides what is open. The Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra is the cheapest way to turn that into something you can measure. You take the open sets and "complete" them: add all <fr:link href="/gtop-0006/" title="Closed Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0006/" display-uri="gtop-0006" type="local">closed</fr:link> sets (complements), countable intersections of open sets (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G_\delta ]]></fr:tex> sets), countable unions of closed sets (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[F_\sigma ]]></fr:tex> sets), and so on.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Why minimal? A bigger <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra means more sets to measure, which is harder to do consistently. The Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra includes exactly the sets that the topology forces you to measure — nothing more.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/boat/" title="Zihang Zeng" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/boat/" display-uri="boat" type="local">Zihang Zeng</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>3</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>11</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://boatnotabot.com/todo-0006/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>todo-0006</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/todo-0006/</fr:route>
                <fr:title text="Intuition: Borel Measure">Intuition: Borel Measure</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>Intuition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
A <fr:link href="/gtop-000C/" title="Borel Measure" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000C/" display-uri="gtop-000C" type="local">Borel measure</fr:link> assigns "sizes" (lengths, areas, volumes, probabilities) to sets built from <fr:link href="/gtop-0005/" title="Open Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0005/" display-uri="gtop-0005" type="local">open sets</fr:link>.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
The <fr:link href="/gtop-0002/" title="Topological Space" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-0002/" display-uri="gtop-0002" type="local">topology</fr:link> tells you what is open, the <fr:link href="/gtop-000K/" title="Borel \sigma -algebra" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000K/" display-uri="gtop-000K" type="local">Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra</fr:link> tells you what is measurable, and a Borel measure tells you how big. It is a function that assigns a non-negative size to each <fr:link href="/gtop-000L/" title="Borel Set" uri="https://boatnotabot.com/gtop-000L/" display-uri="gtop-000L" type="local">Borel set</fr:link>, respecting the rule that the measure of a countable disjoint union equals the sum of the measures.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
Why not measure all subsets? In spaces like <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, there exist pathological sets (via the axiom of choice) that cannot be assigned a size consistently. The Borel <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\sigma ]]></fr:tex>-algebra avoids this by only including sets constructible from open sets through countable operations — which turns out to be rich enough for essentially all practical purposes.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
